34// The semantics of IrOpcode::kBranch changes throughout the pipeline, and in
35// particular is not the same before SimplifiedLowering (JS semantics) and after
36// (machine branch semantics). Some passes are applied both before and after
37// SimplifiedLowering, and use the BranchSemantics enum to know how branches
38// should be treated.
39// TODO(nicohartmann@): Need to remove BranchSemantics::kUnspecified once all
40// branch uses have been updated.
41enum class BranchSemantics { kJS, kMachine, kUnspecified };
42
43V8_EXPORT_PRIVATE std::ostream& operator<<(std::ostream&, BranchSemantics);
44
45inline BranchHint NegateBranchHint(BranchHint hint) {
46 switch (hint) {
47 case BranchHint::kNone:
48 return hint;
49 case BranchHint::kTrue:
50 return BranchHint::kFalse;
51 case BranchHint::kFalse:
52 return BranchHint::kTrue;
53 }
54 UNREACHABLE();
55}

270// Used to define a sparse set of inputs. This can be used to efficiently encode
271// nodes that can have a lot of inputs, but where many inputs can have the same
272// value.
273class SparseInputMask final {
274 public:
275 using BitMaskType = uint32_t;
276
277 // The mask representing a dense input set.
278 static const BitMaskType kDenseBitMask = 0x0;
279 // The bits representing the end of a sparse input set.
280 static const BitMaskType kEndMarker = 0x1;
281 // The mask for accessing a sparse input entry in the bitmask.
282 static const BitMaskType kEntryMask = 0x1;
283
284 // The number of bits in the mask, minus one for the end marker.
285 static const int kMaxSparseInputs = (sizeof(BitMaskType) * kBitsPerByte - 1);
286
287 // An iterator over a node's sparse inputs.
288 class InputIterator final {
289 public:
290 InputIterator() = default;
291 InputIterator(BitMaskType bit_mask, Node* parent);
292
293 Node* parent() const { return parent_; }
294 int real_index() const { return real_index_; }
295
296 // Advance the iterator to the next sparse input. Only valid if the iterator
297 // has not reached the end.
298 void Advance();
299
300 // Get the current sparse input's real node value. Only valid if the
301 // current sparse input is real.
302 Node* GetReal() const;
303
304 // Advance to the next real value or the end. Only valid if the iterator is
305 // not dense. Returns the number of empty values that were skipped. This can
306 // return 0 and in that case, it does not advance.
307 size_t AdvanceToNextRealOrEnd();
308
309 // Get the current sparse input, returning either a real input node if
310 // the current sparse input is real, or the given {empty_value} if the
311 // current sparse input is empty.
312 Node* Get(Node* empty_value) const {
313 return IsReal() ? GetReal() : empty_value;
314 }
315
316 // True if the current sparse input is a real input node.
317 bool IsReal() const;
318
319 // True if the current sparse input is an empty value.
320 bool IsEmpty() const { return !IsReal(); }
321
322 // True if the iterator has reached the end of the sparse inputs.
323 bool IsEnd() const;
324
325 private:
326 BitMaskType bit_mask_;
327 Node* parent_;
328 int real_index_;
329 };
330
331 explicit SparseInputMask(BitMaskType bit_mask) : bit_mask_(bit_mask) {}
332
333 // Provides a SparseInputMask representing a dense input set.
334 static SparseInputMask Dense() { return SparseInputMask(kDenseBitMask); }
335
336 BitMaskType mask() const { return bit_mask_; }
337
338 bool IsDense() const { return bit_mask_ == SparseInputMask::kDenseBitMask; }
339
340 // Counts how many real values are in the sparse array. Only valid for
341 // non-dense masks.
342 int CountReal() const;
343
344 // Returns an iterator over the sparse inputs of {node}.
345 InputIterator IterateOverInputs(Node* node);
346
347 private:
348 //
349 // The sparse input mask has a bitmask specifying if the node's inputs are
350 // represented sparsely. If the bitmask value is 0, then the inputs are dense;
351 // otherwise, they should be interpreted as follows:
352 //
353 // * The bitmask represents which values are real, with 1 for real values
354 // and 0 for empty values.
355 // * The inputs to the node are the real values, in the order of the 1s from
356 // least- to most-significant.
357 // * The top bit of the bitmask is a guard indicating the end of the values,
358 // whether real or empty (and is not representative of a real input
359 // itself). This is used so that we don't have to additionally store a
360 // value count.
361 //
362 // So, for N 1s in the bitmask, there are N - 1 inputs into the node.
363 BitMaskType bit_mask_;
364};
365
366bool operator==(SparseInputMask const& lhs, SparseInputMask const& rhs);
367bool operator!=(SparseInputMask const& lhs, SparseInputMask const& rhs);
368

416// The ArgumentsElementsState and ArgumentsLengthState can describe the layout
417// for backing stores of arguments objects of various types:
418//
419// +------------------------------------+
420// - kUnmappedArguments: | arg0, ... argK-1, argK, ... argN-1 | {length:N}
421// +------------------------------------+
422// +------------------------------------+
423// - kMappedArguments: | hole, ... hole, argK, ... argN-1 | {length:N}
424// +------------------------------------+
425// +------------------+
426// - kRestParameter: | argK, ... argN-1 | {length:N-K}
427// +------------------+
428//
429// Here {K} represents the number for formal parameters of the active function,
430// whereas {N} represents the actual number of arguments passed at runtime.
431// Note that {N < K} can happen and causes {K} to be capped accordingly.
432//
433// Also note that it is possible for an arguments object of {kMappedArguments}
434// type to carry a backing store of {kUnappedArguments} type when {K == 0}.
435using ArgumentsStateType = CreateArgumentsType;
436
437ArgumentsStateType ArgumentsStateTypeOf(Operator const*) V8_WARN_UNUSED_RESULT;
438
439uint32_t ObjectIdOf(Operator const*);
440
441MachineRepresentation DeadValueRepresentationOf(Operator const*)
442 V8_WARN_UNUSED_RESULT;

675// Node wrappers.
676
677class CommonNodeWrapperBase : public NodeWrapper {
678 public:
679 explicit constexpr CommonNodeWrapperBase(Node* node) : NodeWrapper(node) {}
680
681 // Valid iff this node has exactly one effect input.
682 Effect effect() const {
683 DCHECK_EQ(node()->op()->EffectInputCount(), 1);
684 return Effect{NodeProperties::GetEffectInput(node())};
685 }
686
687 // Valid iff this node has exactly one control input.
688 Control control() const {
689 DCHECK_EQ(node()->op()->ControlInputCount(), 1);
690 return Control{NodeProperties::GetControlInput(node())};
691 }
692};
693
694#define DEFINE_INPUT_ACCESSORS(Name, name, TheIndex, Type) \
695 static constexpr int Name##Index() { return TheIndex; } \
696 TNode<Type> name() const { \
697 return TNode<Type>::UncheckedCast( \
698 NodeProperties::GetValueInput(node(), TheIndex)); \
699 }
700
701// TODO(jgruber): This class doesn't match the usual OpcodeNode naming
702// convention for historical reasons (it was originally a very basic typed node
703// wrapper similar to Effect and Control). Consider updating the name, with low
704// priority.
705class FrameState : public CommonNodeWrapperBase {
706 public:
707 explicit constexpr FrameState(Node* node) : CommonNodeWrapperBase(node) {
708 DCHECK_EQ(node->opcode(), IrOpcode::kFrameState);
709 }
710
711 const FrameStateInfo& frame_state_info() const {
712 return FrameStateInfoOf(node()->op());
713 }
714
715 static constexpr int kFrameStateParametersInput = 0;
716 static constexpr int kFrameStateLocalsInput = 1;
717 static constexpr int kFrameStateStackInput = 2;
718 static constexpr int kFrameStateContextInput = 3;
719 static constexpr int kFrameStateFunctionInput = 4;
720 static constexpr int kFrameStateOuterStateInput = 5;
721 static constexpr int kFrameStateInputCount = 6;
722
723 // Note: The parameters should be accessed through StateValuesAccess.
724 Node* parameters() const {
725 Node* n = node()->InputAt(kFrameStateParametersInput);
726 DCHECK(n->opcode() == IrOpcode::kStateValues ||
727 n->opcode() == IrOpcode::kTypedStateValues ||
728 n->opcode() == IrOpcode::kDeadValue);
729 return n;
730 }
731 Node* locals() const {
732 Node* n = node()->InputAt(kFrameStateLocalsInput);
733 DCHECK(n->opcode() == IrOpcode::kStateValues ||
734 n->opcode() == IrOpcode::kTypedStateValues);
735 return n;
736 }
737 // TODO(jgruber): Consider renaming this to the more meaningful
738 // 'accumulator'.
739 Node* stack() const { return node()->InputAt(kFrameStateStackInput); }
740 Node* context() const { return node()->InputAt(kFrameStateContextInput); }
741 Node* function() const { return node()->InputAt(kFrameStateFunctionInput); }
742
743 // An outer frame state exists for inlined functions; otherwise it points at
744 // the start node. Could also be dead.
745 Node* outer_frame_state() const {
746 Node* result = node()->InputAt(kFrameStateOuterStateInput);
747 DCHECK(result->opcode() == IrOpcode::kFrameState ||
748 result->opcode() == IrOpcode::kStart ||
749 result->opcode() == IrOpcode::kDeadValue);
750 return result;
751 }
752};
753
754class StartNode final : public CommonNodeWrapperBase {
755 public:
756 explicit constexpr StartNode(Node* node) : CommonNodeWrapperBase(node) {
757 DCHECK_EQ(IrOpcode::kStart, node->opcode());
758 }
759
760 // The receiver is counted as part of formal parameters.
761 static constexpr int kReceiverOutputCount = 1;
762 // These outputs are in addition to formal parameters.
763 static constexpr int kExtraOutputCount = 4;
764
765 // Takes the formal parameter count of the current function (including
766 // receiver) and returns the number of value outputs of the start node.
767 static constexpr int OutputArityForFormalParameterCount(int argc) {
768 constexpr int kClosure = 1;
769 constexpr int kNewTarget = 1;
770 constexpr int kArgCount = 1;
771 constexpr int kContext = 1;
772 static_assert(kClosure + kNewTarget + kArgCount + kContext ==
773 kExtraOutputCount);
774 // Checking related linkage methods here since they rely on Start node
775 // layout.
776 DCHECK_EQ(-1, Linkage::kJSCallClosureParamIndex);
777 DCHECK_EQ(argc + 0, Linkage::GetJSCallNewTargetParamIndex(argc));
778 DCHECK_EQ(argc + 1, Linkage::GetJSCallArgCountParamIndex(argc));
779 DCHECK_EQ(argc + 2, Linkage::GetJSCallContextParamIndex(argc));
780 return argc + kClosure + kNewTarget + kArgCount + kContext;
781 }
782
783 int FormalParameterCount() const {
784 DCHECK_GE(node()->op()->ValueOutputCount(),
785 kExtraOutputCount + kReceiverOutputCount);
786 return node()->op()->ValueOutputCount() - kExtraOutputCount;
787 }
788
789 int FormalParameterCountWithoutReceiver() const {
790 DCHECK_GE(node()->op()->ValueOutputCount(),
791 kExtraOutputCount + kReceiverOutputCount);
792 return node()->op()->ValueOutputCount() - kExtraOutputCount -
793 kReceiverOutputCount;
794 }
795
796 // Note these functions don't return the index of the Start output; instead
797 // they return the index assigned to the Parameter node.
798 // TODO(jgruber): Consider unifying the two.
799 int NewTargetParameterIndex() const {
800 return Linkage::GetJSCallNewTargetParamIndex(FormalParameterCount());
801 }
802 int ArgCountParameterIndex() const {
803 return Linkage::GetJSCallArgCountParamIndex(FormalParameterCount());
804 }
805 int ContextParameterIndex() const {
806 return Linkage::GetJSCallContextParamIndex(FormalParameterCount());
807 }
808
809 // TODO(jgruber): Remove this function and use
810 // Linkage::GetJSCallContextParamIndex instead. This currently doesn't work
811 // because tests don't create valid Start nodes - for example, they may add
812 // only two context outputs (and not the closure, new target, argc). Once
813 // tests are fixed, remove this function.
814 int ContextParameterIndex_MaybeNonStandardLayout() const {
815 // The context is always the last parameter to a JavaScript function, and
816 // {Parameter} indices start at -1, so value outputs of {Start} look like
817 // this: closure, receiver, param0, ..., paramN, context.
818 //
819 // TODO(jgruber): This function is called from spots that operate on
820 // CSA/Torque graphs; Start node layout appears to be different there.
821 // These should be unified to avoid confusion. Once done, enable this
822 // DCHECK: DCHECK_EQ(LastOutputIndex(), ContextOutputIndex());
823 return node()->op()->ValueOutputCount() - 2;
824 }
825 int LastParameterIndex_MaybeNonStandardLayout() const {
826 return ContextParameterIndex_MaybeNonStandardLayout();
827 }
828
829 // Unlike ContextParameterIndex_MaybeNonStandardLayout above, these return
830 // output indices (and not the index assigned to a Parameter).
831 int NewTargetOutputIndex() const {
832 // Indices assigned to parameters are off-by-one (Parameters indices start
833 // at -1).
834 // TODO(jgruber): Consider starting at 0.
835 DCHECK_EQ(Linkage::GetJSCallNewTargetParamIndex(FormalParameterCount()) + 1,
836 node()->op()->ValueOutputCount() - 3);
837 return node()->op()->ValueOutputCount() - 3;
838 }
839 int ArgCountOutputIndex() const {
840 // Indices assigned to parameters are off-by-one (Parameters indices start
841 // at -1).
842 // TODO(jgruber): Consider starting at 0.
843 DCHECK_EQ(Linkage::GetJSCallArgCountParamIndex(FormalParameterCount()) + 1,
844 node()->op()->ValueOutputCount() - 2);
845 return node()->op()->ValueOutputCount() - 2;
846 }
847 int ContextOutputIndex() const {
848 // Indices assigned to parameters are off-by-one (Parameters indices start
849 // at -1).
850 // TODO(jgruber): Consider starting at 0.
851 DCHECK_EQ(Linkage::GetJSCallContextParamIndex(FormalParameterCount()) + 1,
852 node()->op()->ValueOutputCount() - 1);
853 return node()->op()->ValueOutputCount() - 1;
854 }
855 int LastOutputIndex() const { return ContextOutputIndex(); }
856};
